              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">TikTok’s time ticks</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The future of TikTok in the U.S. hangs in the balance following a recent <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/12/07/tech/tiktok-ban-law-ruling-whats-next/index.html" target="_blank">court ruling</a> upholding a law that would require ByteDance, TikTok’s Chinese parent company, to divest ownership of the app or face a nationwide ban by January 19, 2025.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">TikTok plans to appeal to the Supreme Court, possibly requesting a stay to delay enforcement. While the ruling increases the chances of a ban, there are still options for delay, including political intervention from President-elect Donald Trump, who could seek to protect TikTok. If the ban proceeds, app stores could face fines, and users may experience functionality issues without updates. TikTok creators and businesses are concerned about losing their audiences and revenue, while others remain cautiously hopeful that a ban won’t happen.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
